import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


# Load data
df = pd.read_csv('merged_df_final.csv')

# 1. Data types and missing value summary
data_types = df.dtypes
missing_counts = df.isnull().sum()
missing_percent = df.isnull().mean() * 100
summary_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Data Type': data_types,
    'Missing Count': missing_counts,
    'Missing Rate (%)': missing_percent
})
print('Data Types & Missing Value Summary', summary_df)

# Step 1: Univariate Analysis - Histograms with KDE for core variables

    'deposit_amount', 'withdrawal_amount', 
    'end_of_day_balance', 'daily_txn_count', 
    'customer_count'
]
for var in core_vars:
    if var in df.columns:
        plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
        df[var].hist(density=True, bins=30)
        df[var].plot.kde()

        plt.xlabel(var)
        plt.ylabel('Density')
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

import numpy as np

# Core variables to transform
core_vars = [
    'deposit_amount', 'withdrawal_amount', 
    'end_of_day_balance', 'daily_txn_count', 
    'customer_count'
]
existing_core = [v for v in core_vars if v in df.columns]

# Apply log1p transformation
df_log = np.log1p(df[existing_core])

# Univariate analysis on log-transformed data
for var in existing_core:
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    df_log[var].hist(density=True, bins=30)
    df_log[var].plot.kde()
    plt.title(f'Log1p Distribution of {var}')
    plt.xlabel(f'log1p({var})')
    plt.ylabel('Density')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

# Load and prepare data

# Log-transform variables

          'daily_txn_count', 'customer_count']
for col in to_log:
    df[f'{col}_log'] = np.log1p(df[col])

# Correlation analysis on log-transformed variables
log_cols = [f'{col}_log' for col in to_log]
pearson_corr = df[log_cols].corr(method='pearson')
spearman_corr = df[log_cols].corr(method='spearman')

# Display correlation tables

pearson_corr

# Log-transform deposit_amount
df['deposit_amount_log'] = np.log1p(df['deposit_amount'])

# Compute daily average for weekdays vs weekends
daily_open = df.groupby(['date', 'is_open'])['deposit_amount_log'].mean().reset_index()
pivot = daily_open.pivot(index='date', columns='is_open', values='deposit_amount_log')

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.plot(pivot.index, pivot[1], label='Weekday', linewidth=0.8)
plt.plot(pivot.index, pivot[0], label='Weekend', linewidth=0.8)
plt.title('Daily Avg log1p(deposit_amount): Weekday vs Weekend')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Avg log1p(deposit_amount)')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv('merged_df_final.csv')
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

# Prepare daily average of log-transformed deposit_amount
df['deposit_amount_log'] = np.log1p(df['deposit_amount'])
daily = df.groupby('date')['deposit_amount_log'].mean().sort_index()

# Compute 7-day and 30-day rolling averages
rolling_7 = daily.rolling(window=7, center=True).mean()
rolling_30 = daily.rolling(window=30, center=True).mean()

# Plot original + rolling averages
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.plot(daily.index, daily, label='Daily Avg', alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(rolling_7.index, rolling_7, label='7-Day MA', linewidth=2)
plt.plot(rolling_30.index, rolling_30, label='30-Day MA', linewidth=2)
plt.title('Daily Avg log1p(deposit_amount) with Moving Averages')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Avg log1p(deposit_amount)')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Seasonal decomposition (annual seasonality assumed period=365)
decomp = seasonal_decompose(daily, model='additive', period=365)
fig = decomp.plot()
fig.set_size_inches(12, 8)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv('merged_df_final.csv')

# Log-transform relevant variables
df['deposit_log'] = np.log1p(df['deposit_amount'])
df['withdrawal_log'] = np.log1p(df['withdrawal_amount'])
df['customer_log'] = np.log1p(df['customer_count'])
df['daily_txn_log'] = np.log1p(df['daily_txn_count'])
df['scheduled_deposit_log'] = np.log1p(df['scheduled_deposit_amount'])

# Step 1: Correlation matrices
log_cols = ['deposit_log', 'withdrawal_log', 'customer_log', 'daily_txn_log', 'scheduled_deposit_log']
pearson_corr = df[log_cols].corr(method='pearson')
spearman_corr = df[log_cols].corr(method='spearman')

print('Pearson Correlation Matrix (log-transformed)', pearson_corr)
print('Spearman Correlation Matrix (log-transformed)', spearman_corr)

# Heatmap of Pearson correlations
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
plt.imshow(pearson_corr, cmap='coolwarm', vmin=-1, vmax=1)
plt.colorbar(fraction=0.046, pad=0.04)
plt.xticks(range(len(log_cols)), log_cols, rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.yticks(range(len(log_cols)), log_cols)
plt.title('Pearson Corr Heatmap')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Step 2: Scatter plots with regression lines
top_vars = ['withdrawal_log', 'customer_log', 'scheduled_deposit_log']
for var in top_vars:
    sample = df.sample(n=5000, random_state=42)
    x = sample[var]
    y = sample['deposit_log']
    # Fit linear model
    m, b = np.polyfit(df[var], df['deposit_log'], 1)
    xs = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), 100)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plt.scatter(x, y, s=5, alpha=0.3)
    plt.plot(xs, m * xs + b, linewidth=2)
    plt.title(f'Deposit vs {var}')
    plt.xlabel(var)
    plt.ylabel('deposit_log')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
